  Prompt Structure
  \[[04:23](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ysPbXH0LpIE&t=263s)\] State the task description, role, and goal upfront — Clearly defines the model's objective.
  
  \[[04:34](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ysPbXH0LpIE&t=274s)\] Provide the dynamic content (e.g., images, user query) — Gives the model the raw material to work with.
  
  \[[04:45](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ysPbXH0LpIE&t=285s)\] Give detailed, step-by-step instructions — Guides the model's reasoning process.
  
  \[[04:56](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ysPbXH0LpIE&t=296s)\] Provide "few-shot" examples of content and the ideal response — Steers the model toward the correct output for tricky cases.
  
  \[[05:08](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ysPbXH0LpIE&t=308s)\] Repeat critical instructions at the end of the prompt — Emphasizes the most important constraints.
  
  Task & Tone Context
  \[[05:53](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ysPbXH0LpIE&t=353s)\] Add clear-cut instructions about the specific scenario — Prevents the model from making incorrect assumptions or errors.
  
  \[[06:04](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ysPbXH0LpIE&t=364s)\] Instruct the model to remain factual and confident — Prevents guessing and ensures it only states what it can confidently assess.
  
  \[[07:36](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ysPbXH0LpIE&t=456s)\] Specify when not to make an assessment (e.g., if not fully confident) — Ensures the model reports uncertainty instead of hallucinating.
  
  Background & Data
  \[[09:03](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ysPbXH0LpIE&t=543s)\] Provide stable, known information (like a form's structure) in the system prompt — Stops the model from re-analyzing static details on every run.
  
  \[[09:23](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ysPbXH0LpIE&t=563s)\] Use prompt caching for static, reusable information — Saves tokens and reduces latency.
  
  \[[11:13](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ysPbXH0LpIE&t=673s)\] Pre-load all known details about data (e.g., form row meanings) — Improves analysis and stops the model from narrating its discovery process.
  
  \[[11:30](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ysPbXH0LpIE&t=690s&pp=0gcJCTAAlc8ueATH)\] Provide context on how data is created (e.g., "humans are filling this form") — Helps the model anticipate and correctly interpret imperfect input.
  
  Structural Formatting
  \[[10:15](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ysPbXH0LpIE&t=615s)\] Use delimiters like XML tags (e.g., <data\_to\_analyze>) — Helps the model organize, differentiate, and refer back to specific pieces of information.
  
  Few-Shot Examples
  \[[13:10](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ysPbXH0LpIE&t=790s)\] Add examples of tricky or edge-case scenarios with correct outcomes — Pushes the model to get complex or nuanced cases right.
  
  \[[13:38](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ysPbXH0LpIE&t=818s)\] Bake human-labeled data and ideal reasoning steps into examples — Provides a clear template for the model to follow.
  
  Reasoning & Instructions
  \[[16:06](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ysPbXH0LpIE&t=966s)\] Add a final reminder of important guidelines (e.g., "do not invent details") — Prevents hallucinations and fabrication.
  
  \[[16:45](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ysPbXH0LpIE&t=1005s)\] Instruct the model to refer back to source data for any factual claims — Forces the model to show its work and base claims on evidence.
  
  \[[17:33](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ysPbXH0LpIE&t=1053s)\] Define the specific order for analyzing information (e.g., form first, then sketch) — Ensures a logical reasoning flow that builds context correctly.
  
  \[[18:08](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ysPbXH0LpIE&t=1088s)\] Instruct the model to use factual data (the form) to interpret ambiguous data (the sketch) — Improves the accuracy of its final assessment.
  
  Output Formatting
  \[[20:22](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ysPbXH0LpIE&t=1222s)\] Request a specific output format (e.g., JSON) — Makes the output programmatically parsable for use in downstream applications.
  
  \[[21:15](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ysPbXH0LpIE&t=1275s)\] Ask the model to wrap the final, key answer in specific tags (e.g., <final\_verdict>) — Allows for easy extraction of the critical information.
  
  \[[22:25](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ysPbXH0LpIE&t=1345s)\] Use a "pre-filled response" by starting the model's turn with the desired structure (e.g., an opening {) — Forces the model to generate output in a specific format like JSON.
  
