  I often come across this kind of advice on how we might get better results with better prompting structure. However, I use Claude mostly as a brainstorming partner — primarily to explore the unknown. Take an existing mathematical model and find a way to adapt it to be able to address a list of questions (typically with a real world application and in a way that's never been attempted publicly before). Between the known model and the questions, I myself don't have a clue how to bridge the two! — and if I did, I wouldn't need Claude's help in the first place. So, how can I specify all the details?
  
  My "conversational" approach, for all its limitations, has thus far served be reasonably well, but the more recent Claude models seem to be making surprisingly silly inferences that I don't recall being a problem before.
  
  But all the same, I learned a thing or two (or three) from this video, so it's most appreciated.
  
